The vigour and boldness of Cratinus' writings is described by Aristophanes (KnightS, 526, sqq., and elsewhere), who was about seventy years his junior, though they were rivals the year before Cratinus' death, 13.c. 453, when he won the first prize, and Aristophanes the third with the Clouds. The satire of Eupolis was also very unsparing, as we learn as well from other notioes as from the story (true or false) that Alcibiades had him thrown over- board at sea for lampooning him. The other writers of the Old Comedy, whom Horace alludes to with respect, are very little known to us. Their names, with those of the writers of the Middle and New Comedy, may be found in Clinton (F. H. v. ii. pp. 36-47), and a few are noticed in Donaldson's Greek Theatre (pp. 106—114). The distinction was invented by the Alex- andrine grammarians. The old ended with Aristophanes. The middle was supported chiefly by Eubulus, Antiphanes, Anaxandri- des, and Alexis, and lasted over about fifty years of the fourth century 1³.c. Of the New Comedy, which the Romans imi- tated, the principal writers were Philemon, Menander, Diphilus (see Prol. Adelphi), and Posidippus, who was the last of the

Greek comic poets, and died about lac. 230. Schlegel (Dram. Lit.
